p.me:
\begin{align*}
                    \dfrac{d}{dx}(x) &= 1 && \text{First derivative, using the power
                    rule: } n=1\text{} \\
                    \dfrac{d}{dx}(x^2) &= 2x && \text{Second derivative, using the power
                    rule: } n=2\text{} \\
                    \dfrac{d}{dx}(x) \cdot \dfrac{d}{dx}(x^2) &= 1 \cdot 2x &&
                    \text{Multiply the two derivatives} \\
                    &= 2x && \text{Simplify}
                    \end{align*}

choice.explanation:
Using f(x) = x^2 and g(x) = x+1, the product rule
                   states:\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^2(x+1)] = \underbrace{\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^2]}_{f'(x)}
                   \cdot \underbrace{(x+1)}_{g(x)} + \underbrace{(x^2)}_{f(x)} \cdot
                   \underbrace{\dfrac{d}{dx}[x+1]}_{g'(x)}

TheoremResource.Text:
If f(x) and g(x) are
            differentiable functions and g(x) \neq 0 , then \dfrac{d}{dx}\left(\dfrac{f(x)}{g(x)}\right)
            = \dfrac{f'(x)g(x) - f(x)g'(x)}{[g(x)]^2}

choice.explanation:
The quotient rule states that \dfrac{d}{dx}
                    \left(\dfrac{f(x)}{g(x)}\right) = \dfrac{f'(x) \cdot g(x) - f(x) \cdot
                    g'(x)}{[g(x)]^2}.

